<section xml:id="sec-length-of-a-vector" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Length of a vector</title>

 <p>
  When we mentioned the length of a vector earlier, we just mean its length as a line segment in space. 
  For a vector in standard position, this is the same as its distance to the origin, which we can calculate 
  using the usual distance formula as follows.
  </p>




  <definition xml:id="def-length">
  <statement>
  <p>
  The <term>length</term> of a vector <m>\vect{v} = [v_1, v_2, \dots, v_n] \in \R^n</m> is given by
  <me>
  \|\vect{v}\| = \sqrt{v_1^2 + v_2^2 + \dots + v_n^2}
  </me>.
  </p>
  </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
  Note that the length of a vector is nonnegative, and it is zero if and only if 
  <m>\vect{v} = \vect{0}</m>.
  </p>
  
  <p>
  We can show that scaling a vector scales its length: for <m>\vect{v} = [v_1, \dots, v_n]\in \R^n</m> and 
  <m>c\in \R</m>,
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \|c\vect{v}\| \amp  = \sqrt{(cv_1)^2 + \dots + (cv_n)^2} = \sqrt{c^2(v_1^2 + \dots + v_n^2)} \\
  \amp  = |c|\|\vect{v}\|
  </mrow>
  </md>
  where <m>|c|</m> is the absolute value of <m>c</m>.
  </p>


  <remark xml:id="rem-length-and-abs-value">
  <p>
  Absolute values are like lengths, and the length of a vector in <m>\R^1</m> is just its absolute value. 
  In these notes, we use the notation <m>\|\vect{u}\|</m> (instead of <m>|\vect{u}|</m>) for the length of 
  a vector to emphasize the fact that we are working with vectors (instead of numbers).
  </p>
  </remark>
  
  <example xml:id="ex-lengths">
  <statement>
  <p>
  The lengths of the vectors <m>\vect{v} = [1, -1, 2]</m> and <m>\vect{w} = [1, -2, 0, 4]</m> are 
  <m>\|\vect{v}\| = \sqrt{1^2 + (-1)^2 + 2^2} = \sqrt{6}</m> and 
  <m>\|\vect{w}\| = \sqrt{1^2 + (-2)^2 + 0^2 + 4^2} = \sqrt{21}</m>.
  </p>
  </statement>
  </example>
  
  <p>
  We can scale any nonzero vector to have length <m>1</m>.
  </p>


  <definition xml:id="def-unit-vector">
  <statement>
  <p>
  A <term>unit vector</term> is a vector of length <m>1</m>.
  </p>
  </statement>
  </definition>
  
  <p>
  Let <m>v\in \R^n</m> be a nonzero vector. Then its <term>normalisation</term> is
  <m>\vect{u} = \frac{1}{\|\vect{v}\|}\vect{v}</m>, which is the unit vector in the same direction 
  as <m>\vect{v}</m>. Indeed, <m>\vect{u}</m> has the same direction as <m>\vect{v}</m> since 
  <m>\frac{1}{\|\vect{v}\|} \gt  0</m>, and it is a unit vector since
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \|\vect{u}\| \amp  = \biggl\|\frac{1}{\|\vect{v}\|}\vect{v}\biggr\|= \bigg|\frac{1}{\|\vect{v}\|}\biggr|\|\vect{v}\| \\
  \amp  = \frac{1}{\|\vect{v}\|}\|\vect{v}\| = 1
  </mrow>
  </md>.
  </p>


  <example xml:id="ex-normalising">
  <statement>
  <p>
  Show that <m>\|\vect{v}\| = [1, 1]</m> is not a unit vector, and normalise <m>\vect{v}</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
  Its length is <m>\|\vect{v}\| = \sqrt{1^2 + 1^2} = \sqrt{2} \ne 1</m>, so <m>\vect{v}</m> is not a 
  unit vector. Its normalisation is
  <me>
  \vect{u} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}[1, 1] = \Bigl[\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}, \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\Bigr].
  </me>
  </p>
  </statement>
  </example>
  
  <p>
  In <m>\R^n</m>, for all <m>i=1, 2, \dots, n</m>, let <m>\vect{e}_i</m> be the vector with 1 in 
  the <m>i</m>th component and <m>0</m> in every other component. The vectors 
  <m>\vect{e}_1, \vect{e}_2, \dots, \vect{e}_n</m> are unit vectors, called the <term>standard unit 
  vectors</term> in <m>\R^n</m>. Note that when <m>n=2</m>, the standard unit vectors are 
  <m>\vect{e}_1 = [1, 0]</m> and <m>\vect{e}_2 = [0, 1]</m>, and in <m>\R^3</m>, the standard unit vectors are 
  <m>\vect{e}_1 = [1, 0, 0], \vect{e}_2 = [0, 1, 0]</m>, and <m>\vect{e}_3 = [0, 0, 1]</m>.
  </p>


